<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="notes-week-05">
  <title>Week 5</title>

  <subsection>
    <title>Monday</title>
    <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-topological-induction">
      <title>Compactness via topological induction</title>
      <p>
        The following technique, <term>topological induction</term>, is an extremely useful proof strategy. In the near term, we will use 
        it to prove that closed intervals of the form <m>[a,b]\subseteq \mathbb R</m> are compact. Later, we will use the same method to 
        show <m>[a,b]</m> is connected, and it can also be used to prove existence and uniqueness of homotopy lifts for covering spaces.
      </p>
      <theorem xml:id="thm-top-induction">
        <title>Topological induction</title>
        
        
        <statement>
          <p>
            Let <m>C\subseteq [0,1]</m>  be a subset. Then <m>C=[0,1]</m> if and only if it satisfies the following conditions:
            <dl>
              <li>
                <title>base case</title>
                <p>
                  <m>0\in C</m>,
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <title>downward closed</title>
                <p>
                  if <m>t\in C</m> and <m>s\in [0,t]</m>, then <m>s\in C</m>,  
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <title>topological induction</title>
                <p>
                  if <m>t\in C\cap [0,1)</m>, then there exists <m>\varepsilon\gt 0</m> such that <m>t+\varepsilon\in C</m>,
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <title>supremal</title>
                <p>
                  <m>\sup C\in C</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
            </dl>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </theorem>
      <proof>
        <p>
          It should be clear to the reader that <m>[0,1]</m> satisfies the given conditions. For the converse, suppose that <m>C\subseteq [0,1]</m> 
          satisfies the conditions.
        </p>
        <p>
          By the first condition, <m>C</m> is nonempty. Since <m>C\subseteq [0,1]</m>, we know that <m>C</m> is bounded above by <m>1</m>. By 
          the least upper bound property for <m>\mathbb R</m>, the supremum of <m>C</m> exists and is in <m>[0,1]</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          Since <m>C</m> is downwards closed, we must have <m>C = [0,\sup C)</m> or <m>C = [0,\sup C]</m>. But <m>C</m> is supremal, 
          so <m>C = [0,\sup C]</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          Finally, the topological induction property ensures that <m>\sup C=1</m>, whence <m>C = [0,1]</m>.
        </p>
      </proof>
      <p>
        We now provide the promised application of topological induction.
      </p>
      <theorem xml:id="thm-compact-closed-intervals">
        <title>Compactness of closed intervals of the real line</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            If <m>a\le b</m> are real numbers, then <m>[a,,b]</m> is compact.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </theorem>
      <proof>
        <p>
          If <m>a=b</m>, then <m>[a,b]=\{a\}</m> is compact since <m>a</m> is necessarily an element of some set in an open cover, and thus is covered 
          by a subcover consisting of a single set.
        </p>
        <p>
          Henceforth, assume <m>a\lt b</m> and let <m>\mathscr U = \{U_i\mid i\in I\}</m> be an open cover of <m>[a,b]</m>. The reader may check the 
          following assertion:
          <blockquote>
            <p>
              Let <m>x\in [a,b)</m>. Then there is an element <m>y\in (x,b]</m> and an element <m>i\in I</m> for which <m>[x,y]\subseteq U_i</m>.
            </p>
          </blockquote>
        </p>
        <p>
          Now let
          <md>
            C := \{y\in [a,b]\mid [a,y]\text{ can be finitely covered by elements of }\mathscr U\}.
          </md>
          We employ topological induction to prove that <m>C = [a,b]</m>, whence <m>[a,b]</m> is compact. The above assertion applied to <m>x=a</m> 
          reveals that <m>a\in C</m>. Downward closure is similarly straightforward: if <m>y\in C</m> and <m>a\le z\le y</m>, then <m>z\in C</m> because 
          a finite subcover of <m>[a,y]</m> is automatically a finite subcover of <m>[a,z]</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          For the topological induction step, suppose that <m>y\in C</m>, meaning that <m>[a,y]</m> can be finitely covered by elements of <m>\mathscr U</m>. 
          Fix a finite subcover of <m>[a,y]</m>. Then <m>y</m> is in some <m>U_i</m> within the finite subcover. But <m>U_i</m> is open, so <m>y+\varepsilon</m> 
          is in <m>U_i</m> for some <m>\varepsilon \gt 0</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          Our final task is to show that <m>\sup C\in C</m>. We already know that <m>C = [a,\sup C)</m> or <m>[a,\sup C]</m>. Since <m>\mathscr U</m> is 
          an open cover of <m>[a,b]</m>, there is some index <m>i_0\in I</m> for which <m>\sup C \in U_{i_0}</m>. By openness of <m>U_{i_0}</m>, there exists 
          <m>z\in [a,\sup C)</m> such that <m>(z,\sup C]\subseteq U_{i_0}</m>. By definition of <m>C</m>, <m>[a,z]</m> is finitely covered by <m>\mathscr U</m>. 
          This means there is a finite subset <m>S\subseteq I</m> for which
          <md>
            [a,z]\subseteq \bigcup_{i\in S} U_i.
          </md>
          Thus
          <md>
            [a,\sup C] = [a,z]\cup (z,\sup C]\subseteq \bigg(\bigcup_{i\in S}U_i\bigg)\cup U_{i_0}.
          </md>
          In particular, <m>[a,\sup C]</m> is finitely covered by <m>\mathscr U</m>, so <m>\sup C\in C</m>. By topological induction, <m>C=[a,b]</m>, which 
          concludes our proof.
        </p>
      </proof>
      
      
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-inheritance-compactness">
      <title>Inheritance of compactness</title>
      <p>
        It can be challenging — or at least tedious — to directly demonstrate that a space is compact. Thankfully, there are a number 
        of ways in which compactness can be inherited by subspaces of or constructions with compact spaces. We explore this 
        phenomenon here.
      </p>
      <theorem xml:id="thm-closed-in-compact-is-compact">
        <title>Closed subspaces of compact spaces are compact</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Let <m>C\subseteq X</m> be a closed subspace of a compact space <m>X</m>. Then <m>C</m> is compact.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </theorem>
      <proof>
        <p>
          Let <m>\mathscr U\subseteq \tau_X</m> be an open cover of <m>C</m>. Define
          <md>
            \tilde{\mathscr U} := \mathscr U \cup \{X\smallsetminus C\}
          </md>
          Since <m>C\subseteq \bigcup_{U\in \mathscr U}U</m>, <m>\tilde{\mathscr U}</m> covers <m>X</m>. And since <m>C</m> is closed, 
          <m>X\smallsetminus C</m> is open, and thus <m>\tilde{\mathscr U}</m> is an open cover of <m>X</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          By hypothesis, <m>X</m> is compact there exist <m>U_1,\ldots,U_n\in \tilde{\mathscr U}</m> such that
          <md>
            X = U_1\cup \cdots \cup U_n\cup (X\smallsetminus C).
          </md>
          It follows that
          <md>
            C\subseteq U_1\cup \cdots \cup U_n.
          </md>
          As such, we have demonstrated that every open cover of <m>C</m> admits a finite subcover, <ie />, 
          <m>C</m> is compact.
        </p>
      </proof>
      <p>
        Next, we will show that the continuous image of a compact set is compact. From analysis, we know that 
        in metric topologies, compact is the same as closed and bounded, so this is a topological version of the 
        extreme value theorem.
      </p>
      <theorem xml:id="thm-cts-image-compact">
        <title>Topological extreme value theorem</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Let <m>f\colon X\to Y</m> be a continuous map and suppose <m>K\subseteq X</m> is compact. Then 
            <m>fK\subseteq Y</m> is compact.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </theorem>
      <proof>
        <p>
          Let <m>\mathscr V\subseteq \tau_Y</m> be an open cover of <m>fK</m>. We aim to show that <m>\mathscr V</m> admits a finite subcover. 
          Because <m>f</m> is continuous, for each <m>V\in \mathscr V</m>, <m>f^{-1}V\subseteq X</m> is open. Since 
          <m>fK \subseteq \bigcup_{V\in \mathscr V}V</m>, we know that
          <md>
            K\subseteq \bigcup_{V\in \mathscr V}f^{-1}V
          </md>
          is an open cover of <m>K</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          By compactness of <m>K</m>, there exist <m>V_1,\ldots,V_n\in \mathscr V</m> such that
          <md>
            K\subseteq f^{-1}V_1\cup\cdots\cup f^{-1}V_n.
          </md>
          Applying <m>f</m>, we see that
          <md>
            fK\subseteq V_1\cup\cdots\cup V_n,
          </md>
          so <m>\{V_1,\ldots,V_n\}\subseteq \mathscr V</m> is a finite subcover.
        </p>
      </proof>
      <p>
        Next up: finite products of compacts spaces are compact. But to get there, we will need a result called the Tube Lemma.
      </p>
      <lemma xml:id="lem-tube-lemma">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Let <m>X,Y</m> be spaces and suppose <m>Y</m> is compact. Let <m>x</m> be an element of <m>X</m> and suppose 
            <m>W\subseteq X\times Y</m> is open and contains <m>\{x\}\times Y</m>. Then there is an open neighborhood 
            <m>U\subseteq X</m> of <m>X</m> for which <m>U\times Y\subseteq W</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </lemma>
      <proof>
        <p>
          By definition of the product topology, openness of <m>W</m> implies that there exist open sets <m>x\in U_x\subseteq X</m> 
          and <m>y\in V_y\subseteq Y</m> for which <m>(x,y)\in U_x\times V_y\subseteq W</m>. This implies that 
          <md>
            \mathscr V := \{V_y\mid y\in Y\}\subseteq \tau_Y
          </md>
          is an open cover of <m>Y</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          Since <m>Y</m> is compact, there exist <m>y_1,\ldots,y_n\in Y</m> such that
          <md>
            Y = V_{y_1}\cup\cdots\cup V_{y_n}.
          </md>
          Take
          <md>
            U := U_{y_1}\cap\cdots\cap U_{y_n}.
          </md>
          As a finite intersection of open sets, <m>U</m> is open, and since <m>x\in U_x</m> for all <m>x</m>, <m>U</m> is 
          an open neighborhood of <m>x</m>. Finally,
          <md>
            U\times Y\subseteq (U_{y_1}\times V_{y_1})\times\cdots\times(U_{y_n}\times V_{y_n})\subseteq W.
          </md>
        </p>
      </proof>
      <theorem xml:id="thm-compact-product">
        <title>Finite products of compacts spaces are compact</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Let <m>X_1,\ldots,X_n</m> be compact spaces. Then <m>X_1\times \cdots\times X_n</m> is compact.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </theorem>
      <proof>
        <p>
          By induction, it suffices to prove that <m>X\times Y</m> is compact when <m>X,Y</m> are compact. 
        </p>
        <p>
          Let <m>\mathscr A</m> be an open cover of <m>X\times Y</m>. For <m>x\in X</m>, consider the subspace 
          <m>\{x\}\times Y\subseteq X\times Y</m>. Since <m>Y</m> is compact, so is <m>\{x\}\times Y\cong Y</m>. 
          As such, there is a subcollection
          <md>
            \mathscr A_x = \{A_{x,1},\ldots,A_{x,n_x}\}\subseteq \mathscr A
          </md>
          for which
          <md>
            \{x\}\times Y\subseteq A_{x,1}\cup\cdots\cup A_{x,n_x}.
          </md>
          Applying the tube lemma to <m>A_{x,1}\cup\cdots\cup A_{x,n_x}</m> implies the existence of an open neighborhood 
          <m>U_x\subseteq X</m> of <m>x</m> for which
          <md>
            U_x\times Y\subseteq A_{x,1}\cup\cdots\cup A_{x,n_x}.
          </md>
        </p>
        <p>
          Behold: <m>\{U_x\mid x\in X\}</m> is an open cover of <m>X</m>, and <m>X</m> is compact, so there exist 
          <m>x_1,\ldots,x_k\in X</m> such that <m>U_{x_1}\cup\cdots\cup U_{x_k} = X</m>. It follows that
          <md>
            \{A_{x_i,j}\mid 1\le i\le k, 1\le j\le n_{x_i}\}\subseteq \mathscr A
          </md>
          is a finite subcover. This demonstrates that <m>X\times Y</m> is compact.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </subsubsection>
  </subsection>
  <subsection>
    <title>Wednesday</title>
    <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-sep-disjoint-compact">
      <title>Separation of disjoint compact subspaces</title>
      <lemma xml:id="lem-sep-compact">
        <title>Disjoint compact subspaces of a Hausdorff space can be separated</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Let <m>K,L\subseteq X</m> be <alert>disjoint</alert> compact subspaces of a Hausdorff space <m>X</m>. 
            Then there exist open sets <m>U,V\subseteq X</m> such that <m>K\subseteq U</m>, <m>L\subseteq V</m>, and 
            <m>U\cap V=\varnothing</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </lemma>
      <proof>
        <title>Proof sketch</title>
        <p>
          The reader should fill in the details of the following sketch.
          <ul>
            <li>
              <p>
                If <m>K</m> or <m>L</m> is empty, then one of <m>U,V</m> can be empty and the other equal to <m>X</m>. Now assume 
                both <m>K,L</m> are nonempty.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Fix <m>\ell\in L</m>. Given <m>k\in K</m> separate <m>k,\ell</m> with open neighborhoods 
                <m>U_k,V_k\subseteq X</m>, respectively, where <m>U_k\cap V_k=\varnothing</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                The set <m>\{U_k\mid k\in K\}</m> is an open cover of the compact space <m>K</m>, so there is 
                a finite subset <m>S_\ell\subseteq K</m> such that
                <md>
                  \bigcup_{k\in S_\ell} U_k \supseteq K.
                </md>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Take
                <md>
                  U_\ell := \bigcup_{k\in S_\ell} U_k\quad\text{and}\quad 
                  V_\ell := \bigcap_{k\in S_\ell} V_k.
                </md>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Verify that <m>V_\ell</m> is an open neighborhood of <m>\ell</m>, and thus 
                <m>\{V_\ell\mid \ell\in \ell\}</m> is an open cover of <m>L</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                By compactness of <m>L</m>, there is a finite subset <m>T\subseteq L</m> such that 
                <m>\bigcup_{\ell\in T} V_\ell\supseteq L</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Finally, check that
                <md>
                  U := \bigcap_{\ell\in T}U_\ell\quad\text{and}\quad V := \bigcup_{\ell\in T}V_\ell
                </md>
                form the desired separation of <m>K,L</m> by disjoint open sets.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </p>
      </proof>
    </subsubsection>
    <p>
      <xref ref="lem-sep-compact" /> immediately proves <xref ref="thm-closed-in-compact-is-compact" /> by taking 
      <m>D</m> to be a singleton.
    </p>
  </subsection>
